  </keywords>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1">TCP Console Overview</para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal">EmulatR serves the console over a RAW TCP socket -- no Telnet option negotiation. Defaults:</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">Host: localhost</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">Port: 10023</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">Protocol: RAW TCP</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Override the port with <text styleclass="Code Example">EMULATR_CONSOLE_PORT</text> (the auto-launched PuTTY follows the port). Suppress the PuTTY auto-launch with <text styleclass="Code Example">EMULATR_NO_PUTTY</text>; the listen socket still comes up for your own client. For a remote host, replace <text styleclass="Code Example">localhost</text> with its hostname or IP.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Port <text styleclass="Code Example">10023</text> is only the default -- the listener can bind any available TCP port. This is what makes running several instances at once practical: give each its own port (10023, 10024, 10025, and so on) so their consoles do not collide. Pick a free port above the privileged range (1024 and up); confirm it is free before binding:</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">netstat -ano | grep &lt;port&gt;</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">When connecting, point the client at the same port the instance was started with.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
